sec.p:
Let us now place our estimation procedure as used in this paper among other methodologies. The most general specification for a regression model, in the sense of assuming as little as possible, is a full nonparametric model. These models do not need a specific functional form to determine the relation between the explained and the explanatory variable(s). Under the assumption of a certain degree of smoothness in the explained variable (Y), this variable is described as a smooth function (saym( )) of one or more variables (X); that is,
               \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $Y=m( \mathbf{X}) +\mathrm{error}\,$ \end{document}
            . The nonparametric estimation of this kind of model (see Härdle1990) can be performed with spline estimators (Eubank1988), local polynomial estimators (Fan and Gijbels1996), or kernel estimators (Wand and Jones1995), among others. The flexibility of these models has a cost; namely, they suffer from the curse of dimensionality. If the unknown smooth function can be assumed to be additive in the explanatory variables,
               \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $m( \mathbf{X}) =\sum_{i=1}^{p}m_{i}( \mathrm{X}\,_{i}) $ \end{document}
            , we reach generalized additive models (Hastie and Tibshirani1990), where interactions among different predictors cannot be included. The assumption that eachm(X

               i
            ) is specified by β
               i

            X

               i
            leads to the classical linear regression model. Obviously, some models combine all these,
               \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $Y=m( \mathbf{X}) +\sum_{i=1}^{q}\beta _{i}Z_{i}$ \end{document}
            +error, calledpartially linear models(Härdle, Liang, and Gao1990, Van Heerde, Leeflang, and Wittink2001), where there is a trade‐off between flexibility and deterministic specifications.

Although nearly all flexibility is lost in parametric models (
               \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $Y=\sum_{i=1}^{p}\beta _{i}X_{i}+\mathrm{error}\,$ \end{document}
            ), in a lot of situations, these coefficients have an economic interpretation. Moreover, usually the aim of these analyses is to study not only the behavior of the explained variable, but the range of values for the coefficients. Well‐known examples are the price and income elasticities in demand and cost equations; labor and capital elasticities in Cobb‐Douglas production functions, where their sum is used for detecting constant returns to scale; and marginal propensities to consume in consumption functions. However, despite the economic interest of these coefficients, time‐invariant coefficient models seem to be very restricted.

