The sequence of unknown coefficients is usually estimated through either the maximum likelihood or the least squares method. However, direct estimation by either of these techniques without further restrictions is unfeasible. One solution to this problem is to introduce some smoothness constraints. Under the assumption that the sequence of coefficients is not random, we need to specify the function that relates the sequence of coefficients with the time index. In this setting, the use of nonparametric methods turns out to be a natural solution. Therefore, we assume that each sequence of coefficients has an unspecified underlying smooth function, which can be linear or not, in time; that is,
               \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $\beta _{it}=f_{i}( t/ T) ,\quad\mathrm{i}\,=1,\, 2,\, K,\, p$ \end{document}
            .

The coefficient estimator proves to be the solution to a minimization of the smoothed sum of square residuals subject to the seasonal constraints:
