The practical problem of choosing control parameters is not an easy task when there are several parameters to set. There are at least three possible ways to select control parameters in a nonparametric estimation setting: leave‐one‐out techniques, plug‐in methods, and penalized residual sum of squares. Härdle (1990) and Wand and Jones (1995) offer detailed discussions of all of them. In our context, leave‐one‐out procedures are computationally intensive and plug‐in methods can be applied only if the expressions for the optimum control parameters are available. To select the different control parameters, Orbe et al. (2003and2005) provide a data‐driven method based on the minimization of a penalized residual sum of squares. The kernel selected is the Epanechnikov, and applying the control parameter selection method in the first subperiod results in a smoothness of
