At first sight,figure 1reveals that the confidence limits of
               \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $\hat{\beta }_{1t}$ \end{document}
            are very narrow and this coefficient cannot therefore be assumed constant over time. It is also quite straightforward to determine that its behavior is impossible to model by dummy variables. Its stochastic evolution over time forms part of the “composed” intercept of (9), whose highest values coincide with the highest sales in the history of the firm, and its evolution generally follows the evolution of sales.

Regarding the estimation of β2t
            and β3t
            , we can say that the confidence limits of the two coefficients estimated in the initial stages of the life cycle of the product (first subperiod, 1907–14) are very wide and therefore can be assumed to be constant over time in this period. In this stage, advertising creates awareness and interest in the new product among new customers who are considering adopting the innovation. The estimated carryover effect (
               \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $\hat{\beta }_{2t}$ \end{document}
            ) and advertising coefficient (
               \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $\hat{\beta }_{3t}$ \end{document}
            ) are therefore relatively low and stable.

In the growth stage of the life cycle, which coincides more or less with the second subperiod (1915–25), advertising becomes the dominant managerial decision variable as it encourages people to repurchase the product. Note that, in this subperiod, the advertising coefficient (
               \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $\hat{\beta }_{3t}$ \end{document}
            ) exhibits the steepest increase. It coincides also with the changes in the advertising message, which focuses on relief for menstrual problems. All coefficients present a stochastic gradual trend behavior in this subperiod, and their limits indicate that this increase cannot be modeled by dummy variables.

The saturation and decline stages are included in the fourth subperiod (1941–60). The role of advertising here is to promote new product uses. The theory says that advertising elasticity is now smaller than in previous periods. However, we do not get this outcome. The advertising coefficient (
               \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $\hat{\beta }_{3t}$ \end{document}
            ) presents surprisingly high values. This could be explained by the fact that these last stages coincide with the fourth subperiod, where the advertising message turns back to relief for menstrual problems (probably the most successful) after the vegetable tonic era in 1926–40.

